translate:
Victorious and penetrating, the spirit finds solace in the hidden depths;
Spiritual springs harbor tigers, ready to pounce at any moment.
Fierce claws raise mountains, breaking them apart;
Hands support rocky hearts, twisting and bending them.
Bamboo mist seems to surround us, almost touching;
The shade of pine trees also covers us, interweaving.
Making those who seek refuge and escape feel even more difficult to part with this true realm.

Beyond the river, I wander through a thousand peaks;
Returning to the Lesser Mountains, I chant my poems.
The peaceful land is shrouded in the moonlight of the northern peak;
The windows look far away, hearing the sound of the woolen cloth in Luoyang.
The stone fissure drips with cold dew;
The pine branches hold a long-forgotten lyre.
In the future, beneath the waterfall, I plan to settle down;
I intend to build my home in this forest.

Drinking cold wine together, we become close friends;
In a foreign land, we meet and become more intimate.
Among the falling flowers, the wind carries the sound of flutes;
Amid the fragrant grass, endless people wander.
At this time, I feel deep longing and sorrow;
How can I bear to hesitate and linger on high?
I think of Feizi, the true immortal;
He would not be caught in the dust below the Mountain of the Head Monk.

In thousands of peaks, there's no path for prosperity and decline;
Who can share this desire for seclusion with me?
Even the minister was dismissed by Lu, what crime did he commit?
The infantryman weeps at the end of his journey, with no way to proceed.
The cypress and pine trees are slim and strong, dripping with autumn dew;
The windows and doors are empty, letting in the evening breeze.
As the mountains call to mind clearer thoughts, the figures fade away;
The clouds from the mountains fly into the thatched cottage, filling the air.

Vast sands for thousands of miles, the sky is dark all day; 
After the battle's end, the gates are closed tightly. 
Newly made swords and spears have become agricultural tools; 
Old clothes are stained with blood, leaving traces behind. 
The rolling north wind sweeps away the bones; 
The blue sky weeps for the souls in the distance. 
Humbly, I feel that my wise plans go unrecognized; 
Ashamed, I wear a scholar's cap beside the fortress.

Inlaid with gold and jade, the mountains are painted with intricate designs;
Birds of paradise sleep in the warm sunlight, their emerald feathers intertwined.
Drunken in the spring courtyard, among the beads and shadows;
Songs and eyeliner gather around the red petals, a harmonious sight.
The strings and silk continue to soothe, despite the irritation of the throat;
The crimson threads hang low, suddenly becoming as dark as night.
The flowers bloom and dance in the night, as the wax flames shine brightly in the sky;
The warm jade cup holds the essence of the phoenix, while the red elephant-shaped dish holds the delicate lips of the apes.
As the stars move across the sky, the chariot passes through the air;
The fire city emerges, ready for the morning assembly.
Cars and horses rumble like thunder, making the spirits and demons fear;
Wearing tall hats and heavy swords, they enter the heavenly gates to meet the true ruler.
Opening their mouths for wealth and rank, they consider it a trap;
Their eyes return to find the guilt of the officials and nobles.
The pearl takes from the dragon palace, leaving it impoverished;
The fat and rich are stripped from the lives of the common people.
The nine fields of war point to the heart, as the power and fortune fill their fists;
I hear that the son of Heaven, Lord Guan, is esteemed, possessing half the world;
There is no pride or extravagance that leads to regret, as the red silk curtains are gathered up.
The broken coral trees still laugh at Stone and Wang, the wealthy rulers of the past.

Along the banks of the Xiang River, desolation reigns;
A solitary crane cries in the empty sky, stirring up longing.
I row my boat through the chilly waves, thinking of Fan Li;
I raise my cup to toast the memories of Tao Tang and his wine.
As time passes, I watch the reeds and willows wither, my hair turning gray;
My life is like a driftwood, stuck in a strange land, delayed by the shallows.
Alas, I can't follow the eastward flow to the vast Han River;
My heart and soul are forever tied to the heavens, day and night.

Trying to understand the emotions and intentions, it seems there's no point;
Helping the country with my writings, that's all I can do.
Song Yu boastingly talked about the rain and clouds, but it's all in vain;
Xie An would rather allow dreams to connect than rely on deception.
With a thousand strands of hair in disarray from my travels and worries,
I recite poems by the cold oil lamp, letting the flame burn low.
In this difficult world, I prefer to live in the countryside;
Outdoors, I enjoy being with others and sharing joy and laughter.

In solitude, I chant and sit in harmony;
I cherish the distant thoughts of the Southern Chaos.
Leaving home behind is as light as a dream;
My ordinary heart is colder than a monk's.

Using soup without relying on servants;
Recalling words from a small hawk.
Only relying on ten golden and jade verses;
The loftiest meaning here is not for the common.

Pines and cedars are cold, with many trees dividing;
Leaves float lightly, mixed together in confusion.
Ancient tunes of Shao and Han are taught to whom?
Clear sounds of mountains and waters are enjoyed alone.
In the upper country, the treasure is known to be passed on;
In the old days, friends may no longer be found in the blue sky.
Meet together, do not dislike the wine in the cup;
Drunken and sober, only you remain.

In the end, all my friends are gone; 
Endless dreams occupy my mind. 
Those I cherished in life, I dreamt of last night; 
How many things happened in my dreams, not much time on my pillow. 
We shared a few cups of wine and played a game of Go leisurely; 
When I first saw the Secretary Wei, his golden and purple robe shone brightly. 
Then I met Li the attendant, his laughter was so pleasant. 
Finally, it was Changshi Cui, his mood and expression were deeply attached. 
In one night, three times the situation changed; 
My dreamy heart didn't doubt or suspect. 
This is a phenomenon that people find strange; 
Who can understand this principle? 
I vaguely know this principle, from the Buddhist teacher; 
Distinguishing between good and evil through deluded thoughts, 
The wisdom hidden within is confused by right and wrong. 
If we turn our awareness into wisdom, perhaps enlightenment is near.

Formerly relieved from office three times, a good official like me;
Retired for seven years in scattered places, returning to leisure.
Growing old and retiring is not abandoned by the world;
Poverty is borne with fortitude, thanks to Heaven's compassion.
Wei Jiang goes southward, leaving behind his spring garments;
Wang Shi comes to ask for wine money, serving as a minister.
With enough income for one year, we can enjoy our food and sleep;
Share with you the sweetest sleep and delicious meals.

Carrying the basket out, I forget to return to my room;
The wooden door is still unlatched and the darkness remains.
When I hear guests are ill, I feel ashamed of my health;
In busy places, I realize that my heart is at peace.
I leave the cool autumn temple for incense offering;
I return to the warm spring city to pay homage.
Remember this poem, a wooden bird;
It's between those who have talent and those who don't.

Once an unclean pond, now a clear water pond.
Serenade and songs surround it on all sides;
Tall buildings stand in the center.
As spring arrives, the mist and waves change colors;
Bright trees add to the clear sky's light.
Dragon Spring is truly beautiful;
Don't forget the Midday Bridge Villa.

In the fifth year, March comes to an end today;
The guests have dispersed, and the banquet is empty.
Illness and joy accompany each other in this dwelling;
Spring returns with Mr. Fan at the same time.
Idlely listening to the orioles' songs, I stand for a while;
Thoughts follow the willow catkins as they fly.
The golden belt and waistband lie on the ground;
Year after year, I grow thinner than my clothes.

Worrying thoughts abound, yet balance eludes; 
Fine moments pass by without a chance to meet. 
Waiting for the pleasant sound, stars circle repeatedly; 
In the vast expanse, radiance fades away. 
In times of hardship and sorrow, one dwells; 
Leafless walls embrace the cold, while lights glow all night. 
Plucking the strings of the zither, gazing at the moon's clear flow; 
Soaring cranes drift by, curtains sway in autumn's breeze. 
Recalling the Stone Gate poem, longing for the emerald chicken's journey; 
Fading memories cloud my face, as sweet fragrance hides in the grassland.

Dim and dissolving, we ride through spring's domain.
Reflected in the woods, new leaves unfold; touching the stones, peaks yet to form.
The sun vanishes cold, its rays on verdant hues bestowed;
Clear skies, misty haze, create a picture so admired.
Hazy and fading, deep and shallow intertwined;
Light hues by the stream, shadows and rain intertwined.
Empty now, the forest leaves behind the woodcutters;
On the mountainside, they meet once again.

Rain and clear riverside, willows swaying gently; 
Hand in hand, we share this parting moment. 
A solitary crane and a lonely zither accompany the distant banners; 
Red pavilions and green wine are cherished at the fork in the road. 
In the bright moonlight, I hear the cock crowing early at the inn; 
The flowers are shrouded, while the city gates await our horses slowly. 
At night, I know where to find you in my thoughts; 
Turn eastward, and the breeze brings sorrow that cannot be contained.

In the humble thatched cottage, all things are quiet and serene;
Breeze caresses my head as I gaze into the distance with a far-off stare.
The pines and chrysanthemums in the eastern garden remain, passing on their legacy;
Enjoying old pastimes on the verdant mulberry and elm trees as the evening sky deepens.
We toast to each other's health by the river and admire the bright moon above;
Laughing and chatting about our graying hair in the mirror during the autumn season.
I pour myself some muddy wine from time to time, and welcome any guests who may drop by.

Densely covered with gray hair, I wander through my doorless home;
I welcome and bid farewell to the world with a weary heart.
Pleased with solitude, I have no desire for worldly pursuits;
Self-reliant, I cherish my life without seeking fame or fortune.
Inscribing poems, I yearn for Tao Yin's simple lifestyle;
Ill and bedridden, I communicate with others like Ma Ling.
Content with poverty in the woods, I patiently endure;
Unnoticed by the bustling city, I quietly exist.
